    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-cou2-hemolysis-index-absolute",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Absolute hemolysis index validation — Monte Carlo UQ ensemble vs. in-vitro measurements",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-hemolysis-in-vitro-5op-points",
      "description": "The hemolysis index validation was performed by executing 5 000 Monte Carlo CFD realizations on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, sampling from joint distributions over inlet flow rate (±4 %), rotational speed (±1.5 %), blood viscosity (±8 %), and the power-law hemolysis model coefficients (C, α, β) derived from the Giersiepen–Wurzinger correlation with uncertainty bounds established from the Ding et al. (2015) meta-analysis. Each realization was post-processed using the Lagrangian particle-tracking hemolysis accumulation scheme implemented in the in-house solver HemoSolv v2.4. The resulting 95 % prediction interval for the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) was compared against five in-vitro measurement points obtained from a mock-circulatory loop using ovine blood at 37 °C, with NIH quantified by the modified Coomassie method. Agreement was assessed using the U95 metric defined in ASME V&V 20-2009: at four of five operating points the simulation 95 % PI encompassed the experimental mean ± 2σ, and at the fifth point (6 L/min, 3 500 rpm) the lower bound of the PI fell within 0.6 % of the experimental upper uncertainty bound, deemed acceptable by the credibility assessment team given the known sensitivity of NIH to small variations in shear-exposure path. The campaign was conducted between 2023-11-04 and 2023-12-15 at the University of Alberta Biofluid Mechanics Laboratory. All raw CFD output files are archived in the institutional repository under accession BML-2023-CFD-047. Despite the thoroughness of this narrative, no structured prov:wasGeneratedBy activity IRI has been recorded in this result object; the prose description was considered by the submitting analyst to constitute sufficient provenance documentation."
    }
  ],
